headline: Risk Aversion Sinks Market High Flyers as Fed Cut Hopes Dim

Swaps traders are pricing in about a 50% chance of a cut, down from 72% a week ago, with Fed officials failing to signal conviction for such a move in recent remarks.

headline: 'No playbook' for AI bubble fears, says Deutsche Bank investment arm CEO
summary: LONDON (Reuters) -The explosion in the value of artificial intelligence stocks poses risks to global ​markets for which there is "no playbook", the CEO ‌of Deutsche Bank's 1.1 trillion euro ($1.3 trillion) money manager DWS told Reuters,‌ amid growing concerns that the sector is in a bubble.  The AI stocks frenzy has drawn comparisons with the 1990s dotcom boom and bust, but DWS's Stefan Hoops said today's rally was different as it was being driven by everyday retail investors ⁠– not institutions –‌ and they had yet to be tested.  The Frankfurt-based asset manager is examining whether such a boom could unravel at a faster ‍pace, Hoops said in an interview, adding that the many retail investors sitting on big gains on stocks such as Nvidia could be quick to sell if sentiment soured.

The AI stocks frenzy has drawn comparisons with the 1990s dotcom boom and bust, but DWS's Stefan Hoops said today's rally was different as it was being driven by everyday retail investors ⁠– not institutions –‌ and they had yet to be tested.  The Frankfurt-based asset manager is examining whether such a boom could unravel at a faster ‍pace, Hoops said in an interview, adding that the many retail investors sitting on big gains on stocks such as Nvidia could be quick to sell if sentiment soured.

AI stocks were again at the center of the action, a day after dragging Wall Street to one of its worst drops since its springtime sell-off.  Nvidia, which has become the poster child of the frenzy around artificial-intelligence technology, began the day with a loss of 3.4%.

headline: Bitcoin Slides To 6-Month Low Amid Hawkish Fed Turn
summary: The bitcoin price continued its sharp fall for a second day, hitting a six-month low early Friday but coming off its lows.  The fall in the cryptocurrency and stocks such as Strategy and Coinbase Global comes as markets react to a hawkish shift in Federal Reserve policymaker comments raising doubt about an interest-rate cut next month, despite labor market softness.  Bitcoin's sell-off appears to have added another worry for stock market investors amid concern that financial engineering had begun to propel the S&P 500 and Nasdaq, including Magnificent Seven stocks like Nvidia.
